69
00:04:43,977 --> 00:04:49,262
To visualize reactions between particles
and calculate their probability,

70
00:04:49,262 --> 00:04:53,470
we use a very, very useful tool
which is called Feynman diagrams.

71
00:04:54,890 --> 00:04:59,420
They represent lines of propagation
of particles in coordinates E and p.

72
00:04:59,420 --> 00:05:02,050
Not in space-time but in momentum space.

73
00:05:04,230 --> 00:05:07,990
They also represent the vertices of
an interaction, that is the points where

74
00:05:07,990 --> 00:05:13,370
a force particle is emitted or
absorbed to transmit energy and momentum.

75
00:05:14,520 --> 00:05:19,150
Finally they represent the virtual
particles living between two vertices.

76
00:05:19,150 --> 00:05:21,820
Those have the properties of
their real counter part, but

77
00:05:21,820 --> 00:05:23,280
not the mass of a free particle.

78
00:05:24,810 --> 00:05:29,530
Feynman diagrams are a useful
visualization of a reaction but

79
00:05:29,530 --> 00:05:33,380
also a prescription for
calculating their probability amplitude.

80
00:05:33,380 --> 00:05:36,150
One does that by applying
what is called Feynman rules.

81
00:05:37,570 --> 00:05:42,410
At each vertex energy, momentum, and
quantum numbers are rigorously conserved.

82
00:05:43,670 --> 00:05:49,020
The virtual particle transfers
energy momentum from one of these

83
00:05:49,020 --> 00:05:54,030
particles to the other one, thus a force
act between the projectile and the target.

84
00:05:55,740 --> 00:06:00,320
Details on how to construct a Feynman
diagram will be discussed in module 4

85
00:06:00,320 --> 00:06:04,470
when we talk about electromagnetic
interactions in a quantum way.

86
00:06:07,160 --> 00:06:11,616
For each type of elementary
interaction there is a spin one boson

87
00:06:11,616 --> 00:06:14,660
transmitting the force as
we have explained before.

88
00:06:14,660 --> 00:06:16,650
They are collectively called gauge bosons.

89
00:06:17,820 --> 00:06:21,200
The photon transmits electromagnetic
interactions, the W and

90
00:06:21,200 --> 00:06:24,580
Z bosons transmit the two
forms of weak interactions.

91
00:06:24,580 --> 00:06:27,400
And the eight different
gluons are responsible for

92
00:06:27,400 --> 00:06:29,770
transmitting strong interactions.

93
00:06:29,770 --> 00:06:30,860
To absorb or

94
00:06:30,860 --> 00:06:35,030
emit one of these bosons a particle
must carry the required type of charge.

95
00:06:35,030 --> 00:06:38,520
In our jargon we say the boson
couples to a given charge.

96
00:06:39,730 --> 00:06:41,680
The charge is thus a coupling constant.

97
00:06:42,700 --> 00:06:46,030
It needs electrical charge
Q to couple to the photon.

98
00:06:46,030 --> 00:06:48,340
Q has one component.

99
00:06:49,350 --> 00:06:54,040
It needs weak isospin T and
T_3 to couple to W and Z.

100
00:06:54,040 --> 00:06:55,360
This charge has two components.

101
00:06:56,390 --> 00:07:00,830
It needs color charge R,
G or B to couple to gluons.

102
00:07:00,830 --> 00:07:03,090
This charge has three components.

103
00:07:03,090 --> 00:07:05,830
The probability amplitude to emit or

104
00:07:05,830 --> 00:07:09,770
absorb a gauge boson is proportional
to the charge of the particle.

105
00:07:09,770 --> 00:07:15,430
The probability is thus proportional to
the square of the charge as we found for

106
00:07:15,430 --> 00:07:16,776
Rutherford scattering already.

107
00:07:16,776 --> 00:07:23,170
In the Feynman diagram at each vertex
energy and momentum are conserved.

108
00:07:24,210 --> 00:07:28,020
But do not forget that virtual
particles which relate two vertices

109
00:07:28,020 --> 00:07:31,000
do not necessarily have the mass
of their real counterpart nor

110
00:07:31,000 --> 00:07:34,160
even a real number as their mass.

111
00:07:35,470 --> 00:07:40,020
At each vertex charges as
well as baryon and lepton number are conserved.

112
00:07:40,020 --> 00:07:42,210
Flavor is conserved by electromagnetic and

113
00:07:42,210 --> 00:07:45,630
strong interactions as we stated
before but not by the weak one.

114
00:07:46,810 --> 00:07:51,610
Charge weak interactions transmitted by a
W boson in fact change a particle flavor.

115
00:07:53,260 --> 00:07:56,390
